Introduction to C language

  ğŸ‘‰ C is a general-purpose, high-level programming language developed in the early 1970s by Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs.  
  ğŸ‘‰ It bridges the gap between low-level hardware access and high-level program structure, making it ideal for system programming.

 Why Choose C Over Other Languages?

âš¡ High Performance
  - Close to hardware â†’ faster execution
  - Great for systems like OS, embedded software

ğŸŒ Portability
  -  Code can be compiled and run on different platforms with minimal changes

ğŸ§  Fine-Grained Control
  -  Direct memory management via pointers
  -  Ideal for hardware-level programming

ğŸ—ï¸ Foundation for Other Languages
  - Languages like C++, Java, and Python are influenced by Câ€™s syntax and structure

ğŸ“š Rich Standard Library
  -  Built-in functions for I/O, string handling, math, etc.


ğŸ”¸ History of C Language
- 1969â€“1973: Developed from the B language â†’ C by Dennis Ritchie
- 1973: Used to rewrite the UNIX OS in C â†’ Boosted its popularity
- 1989: Standardized by ANSI â†’ ANSI C (C89)
- 1999 / 2011 / 2018: C99, C11, C18 â†’ added features like inline functions, multi-threading, etc.


ğŸ”¹ Key Characteristics / Features of C Language

ğŸ§  High-Level Language
  â¤ Designed to be human-readable while offering low-level access
  â¤ Abstracts hardware complexities

ğŸ“ Small Language
  â¤ Contains only 32 keywords
  â¤ Simple syntax, easy to learn and use

ğŸŒ Portable
  â¤ Write once, compile anywhere
  â¤ Minimal modifications needed for different platforms

ğŸ“š Built-in Functions
  â¤ Rich standard library (e.g., stdio.h, math.h)
  â¤ Supports tasks like I/O, string operations, math, etc.

ğŸ§© Structural Language
  â¤ Encourages modular programming
  â¤ Use of functions, loops, and conditionals enhances readability and reusability

ğŸ“ Pointers
  â¤ Allows direct memory access
  â¤ Supports dynamic structures like linked lists, trees, etc.

ğŸ§± Extensible Language
  â¤ Users can define their own functions
  â¤ Libraries can be created for reuse

ğŸ”„ Dynamic Memory Allocation
  â¤ Functions like malloc(), calloc(), free() enable flexible memory use at runtime

ğŸ”  Case Sensitive
  â¤ Identifiers like Variable and variable are treated differently

âš™ï¸ Embedded Systems Friendly
  â¤ Popular in embedded development
  â¤ Provides control over hardware with efficient code

ğŸ–¥ï¸ Platform Dependent (Partially)
  â¤ While mostly portable, some system-specific code may vary across OS

ğŸš€ Fast Execution (Compiled)
  â¤ C code is compiled directly to machine code
  â¤ Results in high performance and speed



ğŸ”¹ Structure of a C Program
A C program is typically divided into the following sections:

ğŸ“ 1. Documentation Section
Used for adding comments to describe the program â€“ purpose, author, date, and other helpful info.


/*
 * Program: Example C Program
 * Author: Your Name
 * Date: YYYY-MM-DD
 * Description: This program demonstrates the basic structure of a C program.
*/



ğŸ”— 2. Link Section (Preprocessor Directives)
Includes header files necessary for input/output, memory management, etc.


#include <stdio.h>    // Standard Input Output Library
#include <stdlib.h>   // Standard Library for functions like malloc and free



ğŸ§¾ 3. Definition Section
Defines constants, macros, and user-defined data types.


#define PI 3.14       // Defining a constant
typedef struct {      // Defining a structure
    int id;
    char name[20];
} Student;



ğŸŒ 4. Global Declaration Section
Declares global variables accessible by all functions in the program.

int globalVar = 10;   // Global variable



ğŸš€ 5. Main Function Section
The starting point of the program. Contains local declarations, logic, and function calls.

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");  // Print message
    greet();                    // Call custom function

    Student student1 = {1, "Alice"};   // Structure usage
    printStudent(student1);           // Function call to display student info

    return 0;                   // Program ends
}


ğŸ§© 6. Sub-Program Section (User-defined Functions)
Contains custom functions used to organize code into reusable blocks.


// Function to display a greeting
void greet() {
    printf("Hello from the greet function!\n");
}

// Function to print student details
void printStudent(Student student) {
    printf("Student ID: %d, Name: %s\n", student.id, student.name);
}




